    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, that makes more sense. Thanks. So, looking at the wording \"any and all losses, damages, liabilities, deficiencies... of whatever kind,\" it sounds like they could come after me for pretty much anything. Are there ways to limit this so I'm not on the hook for infinite costs if something goes wrong?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, indemnification clauses can be quite broad, and it's understandable to be concerned about being held responsible for an indefinite amount of costs. To limit this, you can negotiate the terms of the indemnification clause with the Disclosing Party. Some strategies include:\n\n1. **Caps on Liability**: You can negotiate a cap on the amount you would be responsible for, limiting your financial exposure.\n\n2. **Specific Exclusions**: Clearly define what is not covered by the indemnification, such as acts of God, third-party interference, or instances where you acted in good faith.\n\n3. **Insurance Requirements**: You can require the Disclosing Party to carry insurance that would cover certain types of claims, reducing your potential liability.\n\n4. **Mutual Indemnification**: In some cases, you can agree to indemnify each other for certain types of claims, spreading the risk.\n\n5. **Negotiate the Scope**: Limit the indemnification to specific types of claims or to certain actions, rather than a blanket coverage for all possible claims.\n\nIt's important to have a lawyer review and negotiate the terms of the NDA to ensure that your interests are adequately protected.",
      "source": "target",
